# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: guix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:guix/free-software] The right to study and modify a computer program entails that the source code—the preferred format for making changes—be made available to users of that program.
[src:guix/free-software] While this is often called "access to source code" or "public availability", the Free Software Foundation (FSF) recommends against thinking in those terms, because it might give the impression that users have an obligation (as opposed to a right) to give non-users a copy of the program.
[src:guix/free-software] For software under the purview of copyright to be free, it must carry a software license whereby the author grants users the aforementioned rights.
[src:guix/free-software] Software that is not covered by copyright law, such as software in the public domain, is free as long as the source code is also in the public domain, or otherwise available without restrictions.
[src:guix/free-software] Proprietary software uses restrictive software licences or EULAs and usually does not provide users with the source code.
[src:guix/free-software] Users are thus legally or technically prevented from changing the software, and this results in reliance on the publisher to provide updates, help, and support.
[src:guix/free-software] (*See also vendor lock-in and abandonware*).
[src:guix/free-software] Users often may not reverse engineer, modify, or redistribute proprietary software.
[src:guix/free-software] Beyond copyright law, contracts and a lack of source code, there can exist additional obstacles keeping users from exercising freedom over a piece of software, such as software patents and digital rights management (more specifically, tivoization).
[src:guix/free-software] Free software can be a for-profit, commercial activity or not.
[src:guix/free-software] Some free software is developed by volunteer computer programmers while other is developed by corporations; or even by both.
[src:guix/free-software] Although both definitions refer to almost equivalent corpora of programs, the Free Software Foundation recommends using the term "free software" rather than "open-source software" (an alternative, yet similar, concept coined in 1998), because the goals and messaging are quite dissimilar.
[src:guix/free-software] According to the Free Software Foundation, "Open source" and its associated campaign mostly focus on the technicalities of the public development model and marketing free software to businesses, while taking the ethical issue of user rights very lightly or even antagonistically.
[src:guix/free-software] Stallman has also stated that considering the practical advantages of free software is like considering the practical advantages of not being handcuffed, in that it is not necessary for an individual to consider practical reasons in order to realize that being handcuffed is undesirable in itself.
[src:guix/free-software] The loan adjective "libre" is often used to avoid the ambiguity of the word "free" in the English language and the ambiguity of the older usage of "free software" as public-domain software.
[src:guix/free-software] The first formal definition of free software was published by FSF in February 1986.
[src:guix/free-software] That definition, written by Richard Stallman, is still maintained today and states that software is free software if people who receive a copy of the software have the following four freedoms.
[src:guix/free-software] The numbering begins with zero, not only as a spoof on the common usage of zero-based numbering in programming languages, but also because "Freedom 0" was not initially included in the list, but later added first in the list as it was considered very important.
[src:guix/free-software] Freedoms 1 and 3 require source code to be available because studying and modifying software without its source code can range from highly impractical to nearly impossible.
[src:guix/free-software] Thus, free software means that computer users have the freedom to cooperate with whom they choose, and to control the software they use.
[src:guix/free-software] To summarize this into a remark distinguishing *libre* (freedom) software from *gratis* (zero price) software, the Free Software Foundation says: "Free software is a matter of liberty, not price.
[src:guix/free-software] To understand the concept, you should think of 'free' as in 'free speech', not as in 'free beer'".
[src:guix/free-software] In the late 1990s, other groups published their own definitions that describe an almost identical set of software.
[src:guix/free-software] The most notable are *Debian Free Software Guidelines* published in 1997, and *The Open Source Definition*, published in 1998.
[src:guix/free-software] The BSD-based operating systems, such as FreeBSD, OpenBSD, and NetBSD, do not have their own formal definitions of free software.
[src:guix/free-software] Users of these systems generally find the same set of software to be acceptable, but sometimes see copyleft as restrictive.
[src:guix/free-software] They generally advocate permissive free software licenses, which allow others to use the software as they wish, without being legally *forced* to provide the source code.
[src:guix/free-software] Their view is that this permissive approach is more free.
[src:guix/free-software] The Kerberos, X11, and Apache software licenses are substantially similar in intent and implementation.
[src:guix/free-software] There are thousands of free applications and many operating systems available on the Internet.
[src:guix/free-software] Users can easily download and install those applications via a package manager that comes included with most Linux distributions.
[src:guix/free-software] The Free Software Directory maintains a large database of free-software packages.
[src:guix/free-software] Some of the best-known examples include Linux-libre, Linux-based operating systems, the GNU Compiler Collection and C library; the MySQL relational database; the Apache web server; and the Sendmail mail transport agent.
[src:guix/free-software] Other influential examples include the Emacs text editor; the GIMP raster drawing and image editor; the X Window System graphical-display system; the LibreOffice office suite; and the TeX and LaTeX typesetting systems.
[src:guix/free-software] From the 1950s up until the early 1970s, it was normal for computer users to have the *software freedoms* associated with free software, which was typically public-domain software.
[src:guix/free-software] Software was commonly shared by individuals who used computers and by hardware manufacturers who welcomed the fact that people were making software that made their hardware useful.
[src:guix/free-software] Organizations of users and suppliers, for example, SHARE, were formed to facilitate exchange of software.
[src:guix/free-software] As software was often written in an interpreted language such as BASIC, the source code was distributed to use these programs.
[src:guix/free-software] Software was also shared and distributed as printed source code (Type-in program) in computer magazines (like *Creative Computing*, *SoftSide*, *Compute!*, *Byte*, etc.) and books, like the bestseller *BASIC Computer Games*.
[src:guix/free-software] IBM*, filed January 17, 1969, the government charged that bundled software was anti-competitive.
[src:guix/free-software] While some software might always be free, there would henceforth be a growing amount of software produced primarily for sale.
[src:guix/free-software] In the 1970s and early 1980s, the software industry began using technical measures (such as only distributing binary copies of computer programs) to prevent computer users from being able to study or adapt the software applications as they saw fit.
[src:guix/free-software] In 1980, copyright law was extended to computer programs.
[src:guix/free-software] Software development for the GNU operating system began in January 1984, and the Free Software Foundation (FSF) was founded in October 1985.
[src:guix/free-software] He developed a free software definition and the concept of "copyleft", designed to ensure *software freedom* for all.
[src:guix/free-software] Creative Commons and the free-culture movement have also been largely influenced by the free software movement.
[src:guix/free-software] In 1983, Richard Stallman, longtime member of the hacker community at the MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, announced the GNU Project, saying that he had become frustrated with the effects of the change in culture of the computer industry and its users.
[src:guix/free-software] An article outlining the project and its goals was published in March 1985 titled the *GNU Manifesto*.
[src:guix/free-software] The manifesto included significant explanation of the GNU philosophy, *Free Software Definition* and "copyleft" ideas.
[src:guix/free-software] The Linux kernel, started by Linus Torvalds, was released as freely modifiable source code in 1991.
[src:guix/free-software] The first licence was a proprietary software licence.
[src:guix/free-software] However, with version 0.12 in February 1992, he relicensed the project under the GNU General Public License.
[src:guix/free-software] Much like Unix, Torvalds' kernel attracted the attention of volunteer programmers.
[src:guix/free-software] FreeBSD and NetBSD (both derived from 386BSD) were released as free software when the *USL v.
[src:guix/free-software] BSDi* lawsuit was settled out of court in 1993.
[src:guix/free-software] Also in 1995, The Apache HTTP Server, commonly referred to as Apache, was released under the Apache License 1.0.
[src:guix/free-software] All free-software licenses must grant users all the freedoms discussed above.
[src:guix/free-software] However, unless the applications' licenses are compatible, combining programs by mixing source code or directly linking binaries is problematic, because of license technicalities.
[src:guix/free-software] Programs indirectly connected together may avoid this problem.
[src:guix/free-software] The majority of free software falls under a small set of licenses.
[src:guix/free-software] The FSF list is not prescriptive: free-software licenses can exist that the FSF has not heard about, or considered important enough to write about.
[src:guix/free-software] So it is possible for a license to be free and not in the FSF list.
[src:guix/free-software] The OSI list only lists licenses that have been submitted, considered and approved.
[src:guix/free-software] All open-source licenses must meet the Open Source Definition in order to be officially recognized as open source software.
[src:guix/free-software] Free software, on the other hand, is a more informal classification that does not rely on official recognition.
[src:guix/free-software] Nevertheless, software licensed under licenses that do not meet the Free Software Definition cannot rightly be considered free software.
[src:guix/free-software] Apart from these two organizations, the Debian project is seen by some to provide useful advice on whether particular licenses comply with their Debian Free Software Guidelines.
[src:guix/free-software] Debian does not publish a list of *approved* licenses, so its judgments have to be tracked by checking what software they have allowed into their software archives.
[src:guix/free-software] That is summarized at the Debian web site.
[src:guix/free-software] It is rare that a license announced as being in-compliance with the FSF guidelines does not also meet the Open Source Definition, although the reverse is not necessarily true (for example, the NASA Open Source Agreement is an OSI-approved license, but non-free according to FSF).
[src:guix/free-software] There are different categories of free software.
[src:guix/free-software] Proponents of permissive and copyleft licenses disagree on whether software freedom should be viewed as a negative or positive liberty.
[src:guix/free-software] Due to their restrictions on distribution, not everyone considers copyleft licenses to be free.
[src:guix/free-software] Conversely, a permissive license may provide an incentive to create non-free software by reducing the cost of developing restricted software.
[src:guix/free-software] Since this is incompatible with the spirit of software freedom, many people consider permissive licenses to be less free than copyleft licenses.
[src:guix/free-software] There is debate over the security of free software in comparison to proprietary software, with a major issue being security through obscurity.
[src:guix/free-software] A popular quantitative test in computer security is to use relative counting of known unpatched security flaws.
[src:guix/free-software] Generally, users of this method advise avoiding products that lack fixes for known security flaws, at least until a fix is available.
[src:guix/free-software] As users can analyse and trace the source code, many more people with no commercial constraints can inspect the code and find bugs and loopholes than a corporation would find practicable.
[src:guix/free-software] According to Richard Stallman, user access to the source code makes deploying free software with undesirable hidden spyware functionality far more difficult than for proprietary software.
[src:guix/free-software] Some quantitative studies have been done on the subject.
[src:guix/free-software] In 2006, OpenBSD started the first campaign against the use of binary blobs in kernels.
[src:guix/free-software] Blobs are usually freely distributable device drivers for hardware from vendors that do not reveal driver source code to users or developers.
[src:guix/free-software] This restricts the users' freedom effectively to modify the software and distribute modified versions.
[src:guix/free-software] Also, since the blobs are undocumented and may have bugs, they pose a security risk to any operating system whose kernel includes them.
[src:guix/free-software] The proclaimed aim of the campaign against blobs is to collect hardware documentation that allows developers to write free software drivers for that hardware, ultimately enabling all free operating systems to become or remain blob-free.
[src:guix/free-software] The issue of binary blobs in the Linux kernel and other device drivers motivated some developers in Ireland to launch gNewSense, a Linux-based distribution with all the binary blobs removed.
[src:guix/free-software] The project received support from the Free Software Foundation and stimulated the creation, headed by the Free Software Foundation Latin America, of the Linux-libre kernel.
[src:guix/free-software] As of October 2012, Trisquel is the most popular FSF endorsed Linux distribution ranked by Distrowatch (over 12 months).
[src:guix/free-software] While Debian is not endorsed by the FSF and does not use Linux-libre, it is also a popular distribution available without kernel blobs by default since 2011.
[src:guix/free-software] The Linux community uses the term "blob" to refer to all nonfree firmware in a kernel whereas OpenBSD uses the term to refer to device drivers.
[src:guix/free-software] The FSF does not consider OpenBSD to be blob free under the Linux community's definition of blob.
[src:guix/free-software] Selling software under any free-software licence is permissible, as is commercial use.
[src:guix/free-software] This is true for licenses with or without copyleft.
[src:guix/free-software] Since free software may be freely redistributed, it is generally available at little or no fee.
[src:guix/free-software] Free software business models are usually based on adding value such as customization, accompanying hardware, support, training, integration, or certification.
[src:guix/free-software] Exceptions exist however, where the user is charged to obtain a copy of the free application itself.
[src:guix/free-software] Fees are usually charged for distribution on compact discs and bootable USB drives, or for services of installing or maintaining the operation of free software.
[src:guix/free-software] Development of large, commercially used free software is often funded by a combination of user donations, crowdfunding, corporate contributions, and tax money.
[src:guix/free-software] The SELinux project at the United States National Security Agency is an example of a federally funded free-software project.
[src:guix/free-software] Proprietary software, on the other hand, tends to use a different business model, where a customer of the proprietary application pays a fee for a license to legally access and use it.
[src:guix/free-software] This license may grant the customer the ability to configure some or no parts of the software themselves.
[src:guix/free-software] Often some level of support is included in the purchase of proprietary software, but additional support services (especially for enterprise applications) are usually available for an additional fee.
[src:guix/free-software] Some proprietary software vendors will also customize software for a fee.
[src:guix/free-software] The Free Software Foundation encourages selling free software.
[src:guix/free-software] As the Foundation has written, "distributing free software is an opportunity to raise funds for development.
[src:guix/free-software] Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer stated in 2001 that "open source is not available to commercial companies.
[src:guix/free-software] This requirement does not extend to other software from the same developer.
[src:guix/free-software] The claim of incompatibility between commercial companies and free software is also a misunderstanding.
[src:guix/free-software] Red Hat and IBM (IBM acquired RedHat in 2019), which do substantial commercial business in the development of free software.
[src:guix/free-software] Free software played a significant part in the development of the Internet, the World Wide Web and the infrastructure of dot-com companies.
[src:guix/free-software] Free software allows users to cooperate in enhancing and refining the programs they use; free software is a pure public good rather than a private good.
[src:guix/free-software] Companies that contribute to free software increase commercial innovation.
[src:guix/free-software] The economic viability of free software has been recognized by large corporations such as IBM, Red Hat, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:guix/free-software] Many companies whose core business is not in the IT sector choose free software for their Internet information and sales sites, due to the lower initial capital investment and ability to freely customize the application packages.
[src:guix/free-software] Most companies in the software business include free software in their commercial products if the licenses allow that.
[src:guix/free-software] Free software is generally available at no cost and can result in permanently lower TCO (total cost of ownership) compared to proprietary software.
[src:guix/free-software] With free software, businesses can fit software to their specific needs by changing the software themselves or by hiring programmers to modify it for them.
[src:guix/free-software] Free software often has no warranty, and more importantly, generally does not assign legal liability to anyone.
[src:guix/free-software] However, warranties are permitted between any two parties upon the condition of the software and its usage.
[src:guix/free-software] Such an agreement is made separately from the free software license.
[src:guix/free-software] A report by Standish Group estimates that adoption of free software has caused a drop in revenue to the proprietary software industry by about $60 billion per year.
[src:guix/free-software] Raymond argued that the term *free software* is too ambiguous and intimidating for the business community.
[src:guix/free-software] Raymond promoted the term *open-source software* as a friendlier alternative for the business and corporate world.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Differing from traditional package managers, Guix (like Nix) uses a purely functional programming deployment model where software is installed into unique directories generated through cryptographic hash functions.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] All dependencies for each software are included in the input of each hash.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This solves the problem of dependency hell, allowing multiple versions of the same software to coexist which makes packages portable and reproducible.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Performing scientific computations in a Guix setup has been proposed as a promising response to the replication crisis.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The development of GNU Guix is intertwined with the GNU Guix System, an installable operating system distribution using the Linux-libre kernel and the GNU Shepherd init system.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix packages are defined through functional Guile Scheme APIs designed for package management.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Dependencies are tracked directly in this language through special values named "derivations" which are evaluated by the Guix daemon lazily.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix keeps track of these references automatically so that installed packages can be garbage collected when no other package depends on them, at the cost of greater storage needs, all upgrades in Guix are guaranteed to be atomic and can be rolled back.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The roll-back feature of Guix is inherited from the design of Nix and is rarely found in other package managers, since it requires an unorthodox approach to how the system should function (see MicroOS).
[src:guix/gnu-guix] However, the Guix package manager, like Nix, can be used on many distributions like Debian and Parabola.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This also enables multiple users to safely install software on the same system without administrator privileges.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] If the user chooses to build everything from source, an even larger amount of storage space and bandwidth is required.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Inherited from the design of Nix, most of the content of the package manager is kept in a directory */gnu/store* where only the Guix daemon has write-access.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This is achieved via specialised bind mounts, where the Store as a file system is mounted read only, prohibiting interference even from the root user, while the Guix daemon remounts the Store as read/writable in its own private namespace.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix talks with this daemon to build things or fetch substitutes which are all kept in the store.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Users are discouraged from ever manually touching the store by re-mounting it as writable since this defeats the whole purpose of the store.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix - like Nix - has built-in garbage collection facilities to help prune *dead* store items and keep the *live* ones.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The package recipes can easily be inspected (running e.g. guix edit hello) and changed in Guix, making the system transparent and very easy to modify.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Inherited from the design of Nix, all manipulation of store items is independent of each other, and the directories of the store begin with a base32-encoded hash of the source code of the derivation along with its inputs.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix package uses profiles generations, which are a collection of symbolic links (also known as "symlinks") to specific store items together comprising what the user has installed into the profile.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Every time a package is installed or removed, a new generation will be built.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] For example, the profile of a user who only installed GNU Hello contains links to the store item which holds the version of hello installed with the currently used Guix.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] In addition to symbolic links, each profile that Guix builds also contains a union of all the info-manuals, and the man pages, icons, fonts, etc., so a user can browse documentation and have access to all the icons and fonts installed.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The default symbolic links to profile generations are stored under `/var/guix`.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The user can create any number of profiles by invoking guix package -p PROFILE-NAME COMMAND.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] A new directory with the profile-name as well as profile-generation-symlinks will then be created in the current directory.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix package enables instantaneous roll-back to a previous profile generation via changing the symlink to an earlier profile generation.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Profiles are also stored in the store e.g. this item is a profile containing hello above: /gnu/store/b4wipjlsapvnijmbawl7sh76087vpl4n-profile (built and activated when running guix install hello).
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix shell enables the user to easily enter an environment where all the necessary packages for development of software are present without clogging up the user's default profile with dependencies for multiple projects.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] E.g., running guix shell --development hello enters a throw-away environment where everything needed to compile *hello* on Guix is present (GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), Guile, etc.).
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Without the --development flag, only the package *hello* would be installed and not its build-dependencies.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This supplants the guix environment command, which installs the dependencies of a package by default, as it was considered more intuitive for the command to install the specified packages by default and only install development dependencies with a flag.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix pack enables the user to bundle together store items and output them as either a Docker binary image, a relocatable tarball, a Debian package file, a RPM package file, an AppImage or a SquashFS binary.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The Guix graph feature enables the user to view different graphs of the packages and their dependencies.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Guix allows the user to specify additional channels for package definitions.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This feature can also be used to install non-free software and firmware that cannot be packaged in the main project.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] System services, which are defined in the Guile Scheme, enable the user to declaratively compose the configuration of daemons and background services and specify configurations.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This enables the user, within a single configuration file or modularized configuration, to configure the whole operating system (e.g., to have a Tor proxy, an ssh server, and a webserver serving guix-web via nginx on a specific port at bootup).
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The GNU Guix System uses the *GNU Daemon Shepherd*, formerly known as *Daemon managing Daemons* (dmd), as its init system, which is developed in tandem with Guix and is written and configurable in Guile.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] It supplies user-space functionality asynchronously as services, which under Shepherd are generic functions and object data types which it uses to extend the base operating system in a defined way.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] In contrast to systemd, a userspace shepherd process runs as the user.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Central to the Shepherd model of user space initialization is the concept of the *extension*, a form of composability whereby services are designed to be layered onto other services, augmenting them with more elaborate or specialized behaviours as desired.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Shepherd also provides *virtual services* which allow dynamic dispatch over a class of related service objects, such as all those which instantiate a mail transfer agent (MTA) for the system.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] It is intended to be highly programmable by the system administrator using Guile Scheme, but it can also be used to manage per-user profiles of unprivileged daemons and services.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] GNU Shepherd was originally designed to work with GNU Hurd, and was later adopted by GNU Guix System.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Similar to the roll-back feature of Nix, if a system update leaves users with a broken system, users can easily roll back individual packages as well as the whole system state with a single command, `guix package --roll-back`.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This means that the kind of stable channel that is very common in other Linux distributions is no longer needed for users who are willing to report a bug and wait a few minutes, when trying to update via *guix pull*.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] Jesse Smith from DistroWatch Weekly reviewed GNU Guix System 0.15.0 (then named GuixSD), and said, "GuixSD has a package manager that I like", but criticized the limited hardware support and its limited documentation.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The documentation has since then been expanded and improved with videos and a cookbook in six languages with tutorials, how-to guides and examples.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] One area where Guix aims to improve over traditional package managers is in the field of reproducible scientific workflows, mainly in *high-performance computing*.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] In this way, Guix would offer a way to share a reproducible computational environment, i.e., Guix using a recipe for a given scientific software and environment would provide all the information needed to uniquely describe the dependency tree to build and run that software.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] This would not be easy to achieve, for example, in other mixed systems with several package managers for each programming language.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] However, this only provides a necessary but insufficient condition for scientific workflows to be reproducible, as it is necessary to incorporate data collection and processing into the workflow.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] If this is added as part of the Guix recipe, it could satisfy the strict reproducibility requirements.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The project began in June 2012 by Ludovic Courtès, one of the GNU Guile hackers.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The GNU Project announced in November 2012 the first release of GNU Guix, a functional package manager inspired by Nix that provides, among other things, Guile Scheme application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:guix/gnu-guix] On August 20, 2015, it was announced that Guix had been ported to GNU Hurd.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The project has no fixed release schedule and has until now released approximately every 6 months.
[src:guix/gnu-guix] The project migrated away from GNU Savannah to Codeberg on May 25th 2025.
[src:guix/gnu] GNU is also the project within which the free software concept originated.
[src:guix/gnu] Richard Stallman, the founder of the project, views GNU as a "technical means to a social end".
[src:guix/gnu] Relatedly, Lawrence Lessig states in his introduction to the second edition of Stallman's book *Free Software, Free Society* that in it Stallman has written about "the social aspects of software and how Free Software can create community and social justice".
[src:guix/gnu] Before the 1980s there existed a widespread practice of sharing software in ways similar to what is now considered free software where the participants are free to share copies of the software.
[src:guix/gnu] Richard Stallman was a part of a group of developers at the MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory working on the Incompatible Timesharing System, an operating system which was effectively developed as what is now seen as free software.
[src:guix/gnu] This community soon fell to ruin however as the PDP-10 platform which the operating system was developed for was discontinued.
[src:guix/gnu] Development of the GNU software was initiated by Richard Stallman while he worked at the MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory.
[src:guix/gnu] It was called the GNU Project, and was publicly announced on September 27, 1983, on the net.unix-wizards and net.usoft newsgroups by Stallman.
[src:guix/gnu] Software development began on January 5, 1984, when Stallman quit his job at the Lab so that they could not claim ownership or interfere with distributing GNU components as free software.
[src:guix/gnu] The goal was to bring a completely free software operating system into existence.
[src:guix/gnu] Stallman wanted computer users to be free to study the source code of the software they use, share software with other people, modify the behavior of software, and publish their modified versions of the software.
[src:guix/gnu] This philosophy was published as the GNU Manifesto in March 1985.
[src:guix/gnu] Richard Stallman's experience with the Incompatible Timesharing System (ITS), an early operating system written in assembly language that became obsolete due to discontinuation of PDP-10, the computer architecture for which ITS was written, led to a decision that a portable system was necessary.
[src:guix/gnu] It was thus decided that the development would be started using C and Lisp as system programming languages, and that GNU would be compatible with Unix.
[src:guix/gnu] At the time, Unix was already a popular proprietary operating system.
[src:guix/gnu] The design of Unix was modular, so it could be reimplemented piece by piece.
[src:guix/gnu] With the exception of the aforementioned third-party components, most of GNU has been written by volunteers; some in their spare time, some paid by companies, educational institutions, and other non-profit organizations.
[src:guix/gnu] In October 1985, Stallman set up the Free Software Foundation (FSF).
[src:guix/gnu] In the late 1980s and 1990s, the FSF hired software developers to write the software needed for GNU.
[src:guix/gnu] As GNU gained prominence, interested businesses began contributing to development or selling GNU software and technical support.
[src:guix/gnu] The most prominent and successful of these was Cygnus Solutions, now part of Red Hat.
[src:guix/gnu] The system's basic components include the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), the GNU C library (glibc), and GNU Core Utilities (coreutils), but also the GNU Debugger (GDB), GNU Binary Utilities (binutils), and the GNU Bash shell.
[src:guix/gnu] GNU developers have contributed to Linux ports of GNU applications and utilities, which are now also widely used on other operating systems such as BSD variants, Solaris and macOS.
[src:guix/gnu] Many GNU programs have been ported to other operating systems, including proprietary platforms such as Microsoft Windows and macOS.
[src:guix/gnu] GNU programs have been shown to be more reliable than their proprietary Unix counterparts.
[src:guix/gnu] As of June 2024, there are a total of 467 GNU packages (including decommissioned, 394 excluding) hosted on the official GNU development site.
[src:guix/gnu] The original kernel of GNU Project is the GNU Hurd (together with the GNU Mach microkernel), which was the original focus of the Free Software Foundation (FSF).
[src:guix/gnu] With the April 30, 2015 release of the Debian GNU/Hurd 2015 distribution, GNU now provides all required components to assemble an operating system that users can install and use on a computer.
[src:guix/gnu] However, the Hurd kernel is not yet considered production-ready but rather a base for further development and non-critical application usage.
[src:guix/gnu] Because of the development status of Hurd, GNU is usually paired with other kernels such as Linux or FreeBSD.
[src:guix/gnu] A stable version (or variant) of GNU can be run by combining the GNU packages with the Linux kernel, making a functional Unix-like system.
[src:guix/gnu] Most Linux distributions combine GNU packages with a Linux kernel which contains proprietary binary blobs.
[src:guix/gnu] In 2012, a fork of the Linux kernel became officially part of the GNU Project in the form of Linux-libre, a variant of Linux with all proprietary components removed.
[src:guix/gnu] The GNU Project has endorsed Linux-libre distributions, such as Trisquel, Parabola GNU/Linux-libre, PureOS and GNU Guix System.
[src:guix/gnu] Whether the combination of GNU libraries with external kernels is a GNU operating system with a kernel (e.g.
[src:guix/gnu] GNU with Linux), because the GNU collection renders the kernel into a usable operating system as understood in modern software development, or whether the kernel is an operating system unto itself with a GNU layer on top (i.e.
[src:guix/gnu] Linux with GNU), because the kernel can operate a machine without GNU, is a matter of ongoing debate.
[src:guix/gnu] The FSF maintains that an operating system built using the Linux kernel and GNU tools and utilities should be considered a variant of GNU, and promotes the term *GNU/Linux* for such systems (leading to the GNU/Linux naming controversy).
[src:guix/gnu] Notably, Debian, one of the biggest and oldest Linux distributions, refers to itself as *Debian GNU/Linux*.
[src:guix/gnu] Originally drawn by Etienne Suvasa, a bolder and simpler version designed by Aurelio Heckert is now preferred.
[src:guix/gnu] It appears in GNU software and in printed and electronic documentation for the GNU Project, and is also used in Free Software Foundation materials.
[src:guix/gnu] There was also a modified version of the official logo.
[src:guix/gnu] It was created by the Free Software Foundation in September 2013 in order to commemorate the 30th anniversary of the GNU Project.
[src:guix/introduction] GNU Guix1 is a package management tool for and distribution of the GNU system.
[src:guix/introduction] Guix makes it easy for unprivileged users to install, upgrade, or remove software packages, to roll back to a previous package set, to build packages from source, and generally assists with the creation and maintenance of software environments.
[src:guix/introduction] You can install GNU Guix on top of an existing GNU/Linux system where it complements the available tools without interference (see Installation), or you can use it as a standalone operating system distribution, *Guix System*2.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Reproducible builds can act as part of a chain of trust; the source code can be signed, and deterministic compilation can prove that the binary was compiled from trusted source code.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Verified reproducible builds provide a strong countermeasure against attacks where binaries do not match their source code, e.g., because an attacker has inserted malicious code into a binary.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] This is a relevant attack; attackers sometimes attack binaries but not the source code, e.g., because they can only change the distributed binary or to evade detection since it is the source code that developers normally review and modify.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] In a survey of 17 experts, reproducible builds had a very high utility rating from 58.8% participants, but also a high-cost rating from 70.6%.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Various efforts are being made to modify software development tools to reduce these costs.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] For the compilation process to be deterministic, the input to the compiler must be the same, regardless of the build environment used.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] This typically involves normalizing variables that may change, such as order of input files, timestamps, locales, and paths.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Additionally, the compilers must not introduce non-determinism themselves.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] This sometimes happens when using hash tables with a random hash seed value.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] It can also happen when using the address of variables because that varies from address space layout randomization (ASLR).
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Build systems, such as Bazel, GNU Guix, and Gitian, can be used to automate deterministic build processes.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] The GNU Project used reproducible builds in the early 1990s.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Changelogs from 1992 indicate the ongoing effort.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] One of the older projects to promote reproducible builds is the Bitcoin project with Gitian, and later, GNU Guix.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] In 2013, the Tor (anonymity network) project started using Gitian for their reproducible builds.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] Starting in 2011, a reproducible Java build system was developed for the decentralized peer-to-peer FOSS project DirectDemocracyP2P.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] The concepts of the system's application to automated updates recommendation support was first presented in April 2013 at Decentralized Coordination.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] A treatise focusing on the implementation details of the reproducible Java compilation tool itself was published in 2015.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] In July 2013, the Debian project started implementing reproducible builds across its entire package archive.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] By July 2017, more than 90% of the packages in the repository were proven to build reproducibly.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] In November 2018, the Reproducible Builds project joined the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] F-Droid uses reproducible builds to provide a guarantee that distributed APKs use the claimed free source code.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] The Tails portable operating system uses reproducible builds and explains to others how to verify their distribution.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] NixOS claims 100% build reproducibility as of June 2021 for their minimal ISO releases.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] As of May 2020, Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] As of March 2025, Debian live images for Bookworm are reproducible.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] The FreeBSD operating system builds reproducibly and without root access since October 2025.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] According to the Reproducible Builds project, timestamps are "the biggest source of reproducibility issues.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] In some cases other changes must be made to make a build process reproducible.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] For example, some data structures do not guarantee a stable order in each execution.
[src:guix/reproducible-builds] A typical solution is to modify the build process to specify a sorted output from those structures.
